{"title_page": "Partition and secession in California", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:California county map (labeled).svg|thumb|325px|right|Present counties of California]]\n[[California]], the most populous state in the United States and third largest in area after Alaska and Texas, has been the subject of more than 220 proposals to divide it into multiple states since its [[admission to the Union|admission to the United States]] in 1850,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/51st-state-small-step-forward-long-shot-south-233234624.html |title=51st state? Small step forward for long-shot 'South California' plan |author=Daniel B. Wood |date=July 12, 2011 |work=The Christian Science Monitor |publisher=Yahoo! Inc. |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717000433/http://news.yahoo.com/51st-state-small-step-forward-long-shot-south-233234624.html |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> including at least 27 significant proposals in the first 150 years of statehood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://phrelin.com/3Cals/History.htm|title=History of Proposals to Divide California|work=Three Californias|accessdate=July 11, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827231131/http://phrelin.com/3Cals/History.htm|archive-date=August 27, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, there have been some calls for the secession of multiple states or large regions in the American West (such as the [[Cascadia (independence movement)|proposal of Cascadia]]) which often include parts of [[Northern California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.library.ca.gov/collections/online-exhibits/splitting-ca/|title=Breaking Up California: A History of Many Attempts|work=[[California State Library]]|accessdate=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731213511/http://www.library.ca.gov/collections/online-exhibits/splitting-ca/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Prior California partitions==\nCalifornia was partitioned in its past, prior to its admission as a state in the [[United States]]. What under Spanish rule was called [[The Californias|the Province of the Californias]] (1768\u20131804), which stretched almost {{convert|2000|miles|km}} from north to south, was divided into [[Alta California]] (Upper California) and [[Baja California]] (Lower California) in 1804 at the line separating the [[Franciscan]] missions in the north from the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] missions in the south.\n\nAfter the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] lasting from 1846 to 1848, Alta California was admitted to the United States as the present-day State of California. Baja California remained under [[Mexico|Mexican]] rule.  It was subsequently divided into two Mexican states. \n\nIn 1888, under the government of President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], Baja California became a federally administered territory called the North Territory of Baja California (\"north territory\" because it was the northernmost territory in the Republic of Mexico). In 1952, the northern portion of this territory (above 28\u00b0N) became the 29th state of Mexico, called Baja California; the sparsely populated southern portion remained a federally administered territory. In 1974, it became the 31st state of Mexico, admitted as [[Baja California Sur]].\n\n==History of partition movements==\n\n===Pre-statehood===\n{{main article|Compromise of 1850}}\nThe territory that became the present state of California was acquired by the U.S. as a result of American victory in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and subsequent 1848 [[Mexican Cession]]. After the war, a confrontation erupted between the [[slave state]]s of the South and the [[Free state (USA)|free states]] of the North regarding the status of these acquired territories. Among the disputes, the South wanted to extend the [[Missouri Compromise]] line ([[36\u00b030' parallel north]]), and thus slave territory, west to [[Southern California]] and to the Pacific coast, while the North did not.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RDp6AAAAMAAJ|author=Mark J. Stegmaier|title=Texas, New Mexico, and the compromise of 1850: boundary dispute & sectional conflict|year=1996|page=177|isbn=9780873385299|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213103/https://books.google.com/books?id=RDp6AAAAMAAJ|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 1848, Americans and foreigners of many different countries rushed into California for the [[California Gold Rush]], rapidly increasing the population. In response to growing demand for a better, more representative government, a [[Constitutional Convention (California)|Constitutional Convention]] was held in 1849. The delegates there unanimously outlawed slavery, and therefore had no interest in extending the Missouri Compromise Line through California; the lightly populated southern half had never had slavery and was heavily Hispanic.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ellison|first1=William Henry|title=A Self-governing Dominion: California, 1849-1860|date=1950|publisher=University of California Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T8v4nWGB0T0C|language=en|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521235828/https://books.google.com/books?id=T8v4nWGB0T0C|archive-date=May 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Delegates applied for statehood in the current boundaries. As part of the [[Compromise of 1850]], Congressional representatives of the American South reluctantly acceded to having California be a free state, and it officially became the 31st state in the union on September 9, 1850.\n\n===Post-statehood===\n[[Southern California]] attempted three times in the 1850s to achieve a separate statehood or territorial status from [[Northern California]].\n\n* In 1855, the [[California State Assembly]] passed a plan to trisect the state.<ref name=\"Ellison\">{{cite journal |last=Ellison |first=William Henry |date=October 1913 |title=The Movement for State Division in California, 1849-1860 |journal=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly |volume=12| issue =  2 |pages=101\u2013139 | jstor=30234593}}</ref> All of the southern [[List of counties in California|counties]] as far north as [[Monterey County|Monterey]], [[Merced County|Merced]], and part of [[Mariposa County|Mariposa]], then sparsely populated but today containing about two-thirds of California's total population, would become the State of Colorado (the name ''Colorado'' was later adopted for [[Colorado Territory|another territory]] established in 1861), and the northern counties of [[Del Norte County|Del Norte]], [[Siskiyou County|Siskiyou]], [[Modoc County|Modoc]], [[Humboldt County, California|Humboldt]], [[Trinity County, California|Trinity]], [[Shasta County|Shasta]], [[Lassen County|Lassen]], [[Tehama County|Tehama]], [[Plumas County|Plumas]], and portions of [[Butte County, California|Butte]], [[Colusa County|Colusa]] (which included what is now [[Glenn County]]), and [[Mendocino County|Mendocino]], a region which today has a population of little more than half a million, would become the State of Shasta. The primary reason was the size of the state's territory. At the time, the representation in Congress was too small for such a large territory, it seemed too extensive for one government, and the state capital was too inaccessible because of the distances to Southern California and various other areas. The bill eventually died in the Senate as it became very low priority compared to other pressing political matters.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/>\n* In 1859, the legislature and governor approved the Pico Act (named after the bill's sponsor [[Andr\u00e9s Pico]], state senator from Southern California) splitting off the region south of the [[36th parallel north]] as the [[Territory of Colorado (California)|Territory of Colorado]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leo|first1=Michael Di|last2=Smith|first2=Eleanor|title=Two Californias: The Myths And Realities Of A State Divided Against Itself|date=June 1, 1983|publisher=Island Press|isbn=9780933280168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|language=en|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307001017/https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|archive-date=March 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=California|first1=Historical Society of Southern|last2=California|first2=Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern|title=The Quarterly|date=1901|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA230|accessdate=November 10, 2016|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628130547/http://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA230|archive-date=June 28, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sandefur|first1=Timothy|title=Hindsight|url=http://www.callawyer.com/story.cfm?eid=900573&evid=1|accessdate=November 10, 2016|work=Callawyer.com|date=April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006123653/http://www.callawyer.com/story.cfm?eid=900573&evid=1|archive-date=October 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The primary reason cited was the difference in both culture and geography between Northern and Southern California. It was signed by the [[Governor of California|State governor]] [[John B. Weller]], approved overwhelmingly by voters in the proposed ''Territory of Colorado'', and sent to [[Washington, D.C.]] with a strong advocate in Senator [[Milton Latham]].  However, the secession crisis and [[American Civil War]] following the election of Lincoln in 1860 prevented the proposal from ever coming to a vote.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Leo|first1=Michael Di|last2=Smith|first2=Eleanor|title=Two Californias: The Myths And Realities Of A State Divided Against Itself|publisher=Island Press|isbn=9780933280168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|language=en|pages=9\u201330|year=1983|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307001017/https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|archive-date=March 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA223#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=J. M. Guinn, HOW CALIFORNIA ESCAPED STATE DIVISION, The Quarterly, Volumes 5-6 By Historical Society of Southern California, Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern California|accessdate=October 4, 2014|last1=California|first1=Historical Society of Southern|last2=California|first2=Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern|year=1901|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207030747/http://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA223#v=onepage&q=&f=false|archive-date=December 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcet.org/updaily/socal_focus/history/32239-how-southern-california-tried-to-split-from-the-north.html|title=Civil War: How Southern California Tried to Split from Northern California|work=KCET|accessdate=October 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120173650/http://www.kcet.org/updaily/socal_focus/history/32239-how-southern-california-tried-to-split-from-the-north.html|archive-date=November 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* In the late 19th century, there was serious talk in Sacramento of splitting the state in two at the [[Tehachapi Mountains]],{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} because of the difficulty of transportation across the rugged range. The discussion ended when it was determined that building a highway over the mountains was feasible; this road later became the [[Ridge Route]], which today is [[Interstate 5]] over [[Tejon Pass]].\n\n===20th century===\n* Since the mid-19th century, the mountainous region of northern California and parts of southwestern [[Oregon]] have been proposed as a separate state. In 1941, some counties in the area ceremonially seceded, one day a week, from their respective states as the [[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|State of Jefferson]]. This movement disappeared after America's entry into World War II, but the notion has been rekindled in recent years.<ref name=\"latimes-09-2013\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/25/local/la-me-ln-modoc-county-secession-20130925 |title=Modoc becomes second California county to back secession drive |date=September 25, 2013 |first=Lee |last=Romney |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413222754/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/25/local/la-me-ln-modoc-county-secession-20130925 |archive-date=April 13, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The [[California State Senate]] voted on June 4, 1965, to divide California into two states, with the [[Tehachapi Mountains]] as the boundary. Sponsored by State Senator [[Richard J. Dolwig]] (R-San Mateo), the resolution proposed to separate the 7 southern counties, with a majority of the state's population, from the 51 other counties, and passed 27\u201312. To be effective, the amendment would have needed approval by the State Assembly, by California voters, and by the United States Congress. As expected by Dolwig, the proposal did not get out of committee in the Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|title=California Senate acts to cut state in two in districting fight|work=Syracuse Herald-Journal|date=June 5, 1965|page=1}}</ref>\n* In 1992, [[California State Assembly|State Assemblyman]] [[Stan Statham]] sponsored a bill to allow a referendum in each county on a partition into three new states: North, Central, and South California. The proposal passed in the State Assembly but died in the [[California State Senate|State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=JIm|title=Upstate, downstate|url=http://www.newsreview.com/sacramento/Content?oid=10287|accessdate=July 7, 2008|work=Sacramento News & Review|date=January 3, 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128035359/http://www.newsreview.com/sacramento/content?oid=10287|archive-date=January 28, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n<gallery>\nFile:CaliFOURnia map.svg|2003: Martin Hutchinson's proposal{{legend|#c4820e|San Diego / Orange County / [[Inland Empire]]}}{{legend|#003262|Greater Los Angeles}}{{legend|#fdb515|San Francisco / Sacramento/ Santa Cruz / Silicon Valley}}{{legend|#3b7ea1|Northern / Central Valley}}\nFile:Map of California highlighting 2009 Maze CoastWest.svg|2009: [[Bill Maze]]'s proposal{{legend|#008000|[[Coastal California|Coastal or Western California]]}}\nFile:South California proposal (vector).svg|2011: Jeff Stone's proposal{{legend|#f00|South California}}\nFile:Six Californias.svg|2013: Map of the [[Six Californias]]{{legend|#800000|Jefferson}}{{legend|#808000|North California}}{{legend|#008000|Silicon Valley}}{{legend|#008080|Central California}}{{legend|#000080|West California}}{{legend|#800080|South California}}\nFile:New_California_map.svg|2018: Paul Preston's proposal{{legend|#0055d4|New California}}\nFile:Cal3 map.svg|2018: Map of [[Cal 3]]{{legend|#00aae7|Northern California}}{{legend|#00468b|California}}{{legend|#9ac6ea|Southern California}}\n</gallery>\n\n* In the wake of the [[California gubernatorial recall election, 2003|2003 gubernatorial recall]], Tim Holt and Martin Hutchinson proposed in separate newspaper [[op-ed]]s that the state should split into as many as four new states, dividing distinct geographically and politically defined regions as the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], [[North Coast, California|North Coast]], and [[California Central Valley|Central Valley]], as well as the historic [[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|Shasta/Jefferson]] region, into their own states.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2003/08/17/IN81189.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=A modest proposal: downsize California! | first=Tim | last=Holt | date=August 17, 2003 | access-date=August 8, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309152540/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2003%2F08%2F17%2FIN81189.DTL | archive-date=March 9, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Reuters-Hutchinson>{{cite news|last=Hutchinson|first=Martin|title=Califournia Breakup?|url=http://www.breakingviews.com/2009/05/21/California%20break-up.aspx?sg=features|accessdate=February 23, 2011|newspaper=Thomas Reuters|date=May 21, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708092300/http://www.breakingviews.com/2009/05/21/California%20break-up.aspx?sg=features|archivedate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> \n* In early 2009, former State Assemblyman [[Bill Maze]] began lobbying to split thirteen coastal counties, which usually vote Democratic, into a separate state to be known as either \"[[Coastal California]]\" or \"Western California\". Maze's primary reason for wanting to split the state was because of how \"conservatives don't have a voice\" and how Los Angeles and San Francisco \"control the state\". The counties that would make up the new state would be [[Marin County, California|Marin]], [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa]], [[Alameda County, California|Alameda]], [[San Francisco County, California|San Francisco]], [[San Mateo County, California|San Mateo]], [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]], [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz]], [[San Benito County, California|San Benito]], [[Monterey County, California|Monterey]], [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]], [[Santa Barbara County, California|Santa Barbara]], [[Ventura County, California|Ventura]], and [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles]] Counties. It has also been proposed that the state be split in two simply at the straight divide of the [[120th meridian west]], much like its border with the state of [[Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downsizeca.org/|title=Home Page|date=October 23, 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023221939/http://www.downsizeca.org/|archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref>\n* In June 2011, Republican Riverside County Supervisor Jeff Stone called for Riverside, Imperial, San Diego, Orange, San Bernardino, Kings, Kern, Fresno, Tulare, Inyo, Madera, Mariposa and Mono counties (see map, highlighted in red) to separate from California to form the new state of ''South California''. Officials in Sacramento responded derisively, with governor [[Jerry Brown]]'s spokesperson saying \"A secessionist movement? What is this, [[American Civil War|1860]]? It's a supremely ridiculous waste of everybody's time.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8630830/Could-South-California-become-the-51st-US-state.html|title=Could 'South California' become the 51st US state?|publisher=[[Daily Telegraph]]|date=July 11, 2011|access-date=April 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510172347/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8630830/Could-South-California-become-the-51st-US-state.html|archive-date=May 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and fellow supervisor Bob Buster calling Stone \"crazy\", suggesting \"Stone has gotten too much sun recently.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Official Calls For Riverside, 12 Other Counties To Secede From California|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/01/official-calls-for-riverside-12-other-counties-to-secede-from-california/|date=July 1, 2011|work=KCBS|access-date=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716171509/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/01/official-calls-for-riverside-12-other-counties-to-secede-from-california/|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In September 2013, county supervisors in both Siskiyou County and Modoc County voted to join a bid to separate and create a new \"[[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|State of Jefferson]]\".<ref name=\"latimes-09-2013\"/>  Mark Baird, spokesperson for the Jefferson Declaration Committee, is reported to have said the group hopes to obtain commitments from as many as a dozen counties, after which they will ask the state legislature to permit formation of the new state based on Article 4, Section 3 of the US Constitution.  In January 2014, supervisors in [[Glenn County, California|Glenn County]] voted in favor of separation,<ref name=\"latimes-01-2014\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-glenn-county-backs-breakaway-state-20140123-story.html |title=Glenn County is third in Calif. to back breakaway State of Jefferson |date=January 23, 2014 |first=Lee |last=Romney |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623224044/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-glenn-county-backs-breakaway-state-20140123-story.html |archive-date=June 23, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in April 2014, [[Yuba County, California|Yuba County]] supervisors voted to become the fourth California county to join the movement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/04/16/yuba-county-joins-state-of-jefferson-movement-to-split-california/ |title=Yuba County Joins State Of Jefferson Movement To Split California |date=April 16, 2014 |first=Nick |last=Janes |publisher=CBS13 Sacramento |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626223758/http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/04/16/yuba-county-joins-state-of-jefferson-movement-to-split-california/ |archive-date=June 26, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On June 3, 2014, residents in [[Del Norte County, California|Del Norte County]] voted against separation by 58 percent to 42 percent,<ref>[http://elections.co.del-norte.ca.us/elections/june-3-2014-primary-election June 3, 2014 Primary Election - County of Del Norte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608033400/http://elections.co.del-norte.ca.us/elections/june-3-2014-primary-election |date=June 8, 2014 }};</ref> however, voters in [[Tehama County, California|Tehama County]] supported a separation initiative by 57 percent to 43 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/06/04/one-california-county-votes-to-secede-two-counties-vote-to-stick-around/ |title=One California county votes to separate, two counties vote to stick around |date=June 4, 2014 |first=Reid |last=Wilson |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715234933/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/06/04/one-california-county-votes-to-secede-two-counties-vote-to-stick-around/ |archive-date=July 15, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On July 22, 2014, Sutter County voted 5-0 to join the State of Jefferson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.co.sutter.ca.us/apps/agendas/file.aspx?agenda=5717 |title=Sutter County Board of Supervisors Summary of July 22, 2014 |date=July 22, 2014 |first=Steven |last=Smith |publisher=Sutter County |accessdate=July 22, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801095615/https://www.co.sutter.ca.us/apps/agendas/file.aspx?agenda=5717 |archive-date=August 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Six Californias]]: On December 19, 2013, venture capitalist [[Timothy C. Draper|Tim Draper]] submitted a six-page proposal<ref>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Six Californias|url=https://www.scribd.com/embeds/192645393/content|work=Initiative Measure Submitted Directly to Voters|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803170347/https://www.scribd.com/embeds/192645393/content|archive-date=August 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=six-californias>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Six Californias|url=http://www.sixcalifornias.info/|work=Website|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220111359/http://www.sixcalifornias.info/|archive-date=December 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  to the California Attorney General to split California into six new states, citing improved representation, governance, and competition between industries.<ref name=draper-six-californias>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Tim Draper Wants To Split California Into Pieces And Turn Silicon Valley Into Its Own State|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/19/tim-draper-six-californias-secede-silicon-valley-ballot-initiative/|publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220073434/http://techcrunch.com/2013/12/19/tim-draper-six-californias-secede-silicon-valley-ballot-initiative/|archive-date=December 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  On February 19, 2014, [[Secretary of State of California|Secretary of State]] [[Debra Bowen]] approved the proposal allowing supporters to start collecting signatures in order to qualify the petition for a ballot. A total of 807,615 registered voters were needed by July 18, 2014 for the proposal to appear on the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fields|first=Kayle|title=Petition to Split California Into Six States Gets Green Light|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/02/petition-to-split-california-into-six-states-gets-green-light/|work=abcnews.go.com|accessdate=February 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221072359/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/02/petition-to-split-california-into-six-states-gets-green-light/|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 14, the petition organizer announced that the proposal received enough signatures to be placed on the ballot in two years,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chaussee|first1=Jennifer|title=Billionaire's breakup plan would chop California into six states|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-california-breakup-20140714,0,4830203.story|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=Chicago Tribune|agency=Reuter|date=July 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720001146/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-california-breakup-20140714,0,4830203.story|archive-date=July 20, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> however, it was determined that only about two thirds were valid and the petition fell short of qualifying for the November 2016 ballot.<ref>[http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/12/6702457/six-californias-initiative-fails.html Six Californias initiative fails] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927092523/http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/12/6702457/six-californias-initiative-fails.html |date=September 27, 2014 }}, sacbee.com.</ref>\n* New California: On January 16, 2018, the 501(c)(4) organization New California, organized by conservative radio talk show host Paul Preston, published its proposed state's Declaration of Independence. As motivation for the split, they cited that California ranked 48th out of 50 states for business climate and also cited high taxes and California's failure to follow the state and federal constitutions. New California would include the rural counties that make up most of the state's area, leaving the more heavily populated areas around San Francisco, Sacramento, and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite web|url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/01/15/new-california-declares-independence-from-rest-of-state/|title=New California Declares Independence From Rest Of State|date=January 15, 2018|website=cbslocal.com|access-date=January 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123184710/http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/01/15/new-california-declares-independence-from-rest-of-state/|archive-date=January 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> New California would also include the urban areas of [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa County]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], and [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]], bringing the population to around 20 million.<ref name=\"cbs\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Betz|first1=Bradford|title='New California' movement seeks to divide the Golden State in half|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/17/new-california-movement-seeks-to-divide-golden-state-in-half.html|accessdate=January 19, 2018|work=Fox News|date=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119084748/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/17/new-california-movement-seeks-to-divide-golden-state-in-half.html|archive-date=January 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In April 2018, the [[Cal 3]] organization announced it had more than 600,000 signatures to place an initiative on the November 2018 ballot proposing that California should be split into three separate states.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://threestateca.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Press-Release-041118.pdf |title=\"CAL 3\" Initiative to Partition California Reaches Unprecedented Milestone |date=April 11, 2018 |publisher=Cal 3 |accessdate=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414041639/https://threestateca.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Press-Release-041118.pdf |archive-date=April 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The signatures must be verified before the proposal qualifies for the ballot<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/split-California-3-states-Northern-Southern-12830724.php|title=Plan to split California into 3 states may qualify for ballot|last1=Ting|first1=Eric|date=April 13, 2018|website=SFGate|publisher=Hearst|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419072319/https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/split-California-3-states-Northern-Southern-12830724.php|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> - this was achieved by June 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/proposal-split-california-three-states-earns-spot-november-ballot-n882646 |title=Proposal to split California into three states earns spot on November ballot |last=Helsel |first=Phil |date=June 13, 2018 |website=nbcnews.com |publisher=NBC News |access-date=June 13, 2018 |quote=Voters in the massive state of California, touted as having an economy larger than most countries, could decide whether to support a plan calling for The Golden State to be split into three. An initiative that would direct the governor to seek Congressional approval to divide California into three states has enough valid signatures to be eligible for the Nov. 6 ballot, the Secretary of State\u2019s office said Tuesday. If the initiative is not withdrawn, it will be qualified for the ballot on June 28. Even if approved by voters, it faces the hurdle of approval by Congress. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613130540/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/proposal-split-california-three-states-earns-spot-november-ballot-n882646 |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2018, the [[California Supreme Court]] pulled the Cal 3 proposal from the ballot for further state constitutional review.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Splitting-up-Calif-State-Supreme-Court-takes-13085880.php | title=Splitting up California: State Supreme Court takes initiative off ballot | first=Bob | last=Egelko | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | date=July 18, 2018 | quote=[T]he court issued a unanimous order removing the measure from the ballot and ordering further legal arguments on whether it should be placed on another ballot in 2020 or struck down altogether | access-date=July 19, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719100248/https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Splitting-up-Calif-State-Supreme-Court-takes-13085880.php | archive-date=July 19, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2020, \"Move Oregon's Border For a Greater Idaho\" proposed breaking off most of Oregon's area and some of Northern California and join it with Idaho. The areas proposed to break off of Oregon and California vote Republican but in a state whose legislatures are dominated by Democrats. Douglas and Josephine counties in Oregon approved language for petitions to put a measure on the ballot. Even if passed by voters, it would still need approval from all three state legislatures.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/02/24/808916891/some-oregonians-want-to-leave-and-take-part-of-the-state-to-idaho-with-them | title=Some Oregonians Want To Leave And Take Part Of The State To Idaho With Them| work=[[NPR]]| location=Washington, D.C.| date=February 24, 2020| accessdate=February 26, 2020|}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pacific-northwest-news/2020/02/ballot-initiative-effort-to-move-eastern-oregon-counties-to-idaho-gains-momentum-leader-calls-it-peaceful-revolution.html | title=Ballot-initiative effort to move eastern Oregon counties to Idaho gains momentum; leader calls it \u2018peaceful revolution\u2019| work=[[The Oregonian]]| location= Portland, Oregon | date=February 17, 2020| accessdate=February 26, 2020|}}</ref>\n\n==Secession==\n\n===Ecotopia===\nWriter [[Ernest Callenbach]] wrote a 1975 novel, entitled ''[[Ecotopia]]'', in which he proposed a full-blown secession of Northern California, Oregon, and Washington from the United States in order to focus upon environmentally friendly living and culture. He later abandoned the idea stating: \"We are now fatally interconnected, in climate change, ocean impoverishment, agricultural soil loss, etc. etc. etc.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/san-francisco-secession-ecotopia_n_898457.html|title = San Francisco Secession: Could It Create 'Ecotopia'?|author = Matt Sledge|newspaper = Huffington Post|date = July 14, 2011|access-date = July 15, 2011|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110717235335/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/san-francisco-secession-ecotopia_n_898457.html|archive-date = July 17, 2011|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===Cascadia===\n{{main article|Cascadia (independence movement)}}\nWhile mostly consisting of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[Oregon]], [[Idaho]] and [[British Columbia]] in Canada, proposals for an independent Cascadia often include portions of northern California.\n\n===Calexit===\n{{main article|Yes California}}\nIn the wake of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Donald Trump]]'s winning the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], a fringe movement organized by [[Yes California]], referred to as \"Calexit\" - a term inspired by the successful 2016 [[Brexit]] referendum, arose in a bid to gather the 585,407 signatures necessary to place a [[secession]]ist question on the 2018 ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/%E2%80%98california-is-a-nation-not-a-state%E2%80%99-a-fringe-movement-wants-a-break-from-the-us/ar-AAn5LLx?OCID=ansmsnnews11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220093900/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/%E2%80%98california-is-a-nation-not-a-state%E2%80%99-a-fringe-movement-wants-a-break-from-the-us/ar-AAn5LLx?OCID=ansmsnnews11 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 20, 2017 |date=February 20, 2017 |title=\u2018California is a nation, not a state\u2019: A fringe movement wants a break from the U.S. |work=MSNBC}}</ref> In July 2018, the objectives of the Calexit initiative were expanded upon by including a plan to carve out an \u201cautonomous Native American nation\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.stanforddaily.com/2018/09/27/final-hf-calexit-supporters-relaunch-campaign-with-proposals-to-create-a-north-american-nation/|title=Calexit supporters relaunch campaign with proposals to create Native American nation|date=September 27, 2018|work=The Stanford Daily|access-date=November 11, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110220146/https://www.stanforddaily.com/2018/09/27/final-hf-calexit-supporters-relaunch-campaign-with-proposals-to-create-a-north-american-nation/|archive-date=November 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> that would take up the eastern part of California, and \"postponing its ballot referendum approach in favor of convincing Republican states to support their breakaway efforts.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n===California National Party===\nFounded in 2015, California National Party (CNP) is a political party advocating a pragmatic platform. The CNP also seeks, as a long-term goal, the secession of California from the United States by legal and peaceful means.\n\nThe California National Party draws its inspiration from the [[Scottish National Party]], which advocates for the independence of Scotland from the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=California could see new political party with independence goal|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article54004530.html|work=Sacramento Bee|accessdate=March 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308223549/http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article54004530.html|archive-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-californians-inspired-by-scotland-to-pursue-independent-nationhood|title=Meet the California Separatists Leading a New Movement to Secede from the United States|website=VICE|language=en-us|access-date=March 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401202254/http://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-californians-inspired-by-scotland-to-pursue-independent-nationhood|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2016, the California Secretary of State's office sent a memorandum to each of California's 58 county Registration of Voters offices to inform them that they had \"received formal notification from the California National Party of their intent to qualify\" as a political party on December 7, 2015, and thereafter assigned the party a code designation of \"CNP\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ccrov/pdf/2016/january/16013ms.pdf|title=California Secretary of State {{!}} Political Body: California National Party|date=January 6, 2016|access-date=March 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215091539/http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov//ccrov/pdf/2016/january/16013ms.pdf|archive-date=February 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFormal organizing for the party did not begin until June 2016, when the CNP held its first convention and elections in Sacramento, California.  At that convention, Theo Slater and Andria Franco were elected as Chair and Vice Chair. Jed Wheeler, founder of Californians for Independence, was elected Secretary as the two groups merged. The CNP adopted a new platform, based on the Californians for Independence platform, in September of that year;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californianational.party/en_US/platform-california-national-party/#peace-and-defense|title=The California National Party Platform - California National Party|website=californianational.party|language=en-US|access-date=March 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328195126/https://californianational.party/en_US/platform-california-national-party/#peace-and-defense|archive-date=March 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and launched a website, mailing list, and recruitment drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ror/ror-odd-year-2019/nonqual.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323230018/https://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ror/ror-odd-year-2019/nonqual.pdf |archive-date=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The party re-filed with the Secretary of State in November 2016 and the new leadership was officially recognized<ref name=\":3\" /> shortly after.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of U.S. state partition proposals]]\n* [[Secession in New York]]\n* [[Texas divisionism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed states of the United States|California]]\n[[Category:Separatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Politics of California]]\n[[Category:History of California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:California county map (labeled).svg|thumb|325px|right|Present counties of California]]\n[[California]], the most populous state in the United States and third largest in area after Alaska and Texas, has been the subject of more than 220 proposals to divide it into multiple states since its [[admission to the Union|admission to the United States]] in 1850,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/51st-state-small-step-forward-long-shot-south-233234624.html |title=51st state? Small step forward for long-shot 'South California' plan |author=Daniel B. Wood |date=July 12, 2011 |work=The Christian Science Monitor |publisher=Yahoo! Inc. |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717000433/http://news.yahoo.com/51st-state-small-step-forward-long-shot-south-233234624.html |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> including at least 27 significant proposals in the first 150 years of statehood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://phrelin.com/3Cals/History.htm|title=History of Proposals to Divide California|work=Three Californias|accessdate=July 11, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827231131/http://phrelin.com/3Cals/History.htm|archive-date=August 27, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, there have been some calls for the secession of multiple states or large regions in the American West (such as the [[Cascadia (independence movement)|proposal of Cascadia]]) which often include parts of [[Northern California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.library.ca.gov/collections/online-exhibits/splitting-ca/|title=Breaking Up California: A History of Many Attempts|work=[[California State Library]]|accessdate=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731213511/http://www.library.ca.gov/collections/online-exhibits/splitting-ca/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Prior California partitions==\nCalifornia was partitioned in its past, prior to its admission as a state in the [[United States]]. What under Spanish rule was called [[The Californias|the Province of the Californias]] (1768\u20131804), which stretched almost {{convert|2000|miles|km}} from north to south, was divided into [[Alta California]] (Upper California) and [[Baja California]] (Lower California) in 1804 at the line separating the [[Franciscan]] missions in the north from the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] missions in the south.\n\nAfter the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] lasting from 1846 to 1848, Alta California was admitted to the United States as the present-day State of California. Baja California remained under [[Mexico|Mexican]] rule.  It was subsequently divided into two Mexican states. \n\nIn 1888, under the government of President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], Baja California became a federally administered territory called the North Territory of Baja California (\"north territory\" because it was the northernmost territory in the Republic of Mexico). In 1952, the northern portion of this territory (above 28\u00b0N) became the 29th state of Mexico, called Baja California; the sparsely populated southern portion remained a federally administered territory. In 1974, it became the 31st state of Mexico, admitted as [[Baja California Sur]].\n\n==History of partition movements==\n\n===Pre-statehood===\n{{main article|Compromise of 1850}}\nThe territory that became the present state of California was acquired by the U.S. as a result of American victory in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and subsequent 1848 [[Mexican Cession]]. After the war, a confrontation erupted between the [[slave state]]s of the South and the [[Free state (USA)|free states]] of the North regarding the status of these acquired territories. Among the disputes, the South wanted to extend the [[Missouri Compromise]] line ([[36\u00b030' parallel north]]), and thus slave territory, west to [[Southern California]] and to the Pacific coast, while the North did not.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RDp6AAAAMAAJ|author=Mark J. Stegmaier|title=Texas, New Mexico, and the compromise of 1850: boundary dispute & sectional conflict|year=1996|page=177|isbn=9780873385299|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213103/https://books.google.com/books?id=RDp6AAAAMAAJ|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 1848, Americans and foreigners of many different countries rushed into California for the [[California Gold Rush]], rapidly increasing the population. In response to growing demand for a better, more representative government, a [[Constitutional Convention (California)|Constitutional Convention]] was held in 1849. The delegates there unanimously outlawed slavery, and therefore had no interest in extending the Missouri Compromise Line through California; the lightly populated southern half had never had slavery and was heavily Hispanic.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ellison|first1=William Henry|title=A Self-governing Dominion: California, 1849-1860|date=1950|publisher=University of California Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T8v4nWGB0T0C|language=en|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521235828/https://books.google.com/books?id=T8v4nWGB0T0C|archive-date=May 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Delegates applied for statehood in the current boundaries. As part of the [[Compromise of 1850]], Congressional representatives of the American South reluctantly acceded to having California be a free state, and it officially became the 31st state in the union on September 9, 1850.\n\n===Post-statehood===\n[[Southern California]] attempted three times in the 1850s to achieve a separate statehood or territorial status from [[Northern California]].\n\n* In 1855, the [[California State Assembly]] passed a plan to trisect the state.<ref name=\"Ellison\">{{cite journal |last=Ellison |first=William Henry |date=October 1913 |title=The Movement for State Division in California, 1849-1860 |journal=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly |volume=12| issue =  2 |pages=101\u2013139 | jstor=30234593}}</ref> All of the southern [[List of counties in California|counties]] as far north as [[Monterey County|Monterey]], [[Merced County|Merced]], and part of [[Mariposa County|Mariposa]], then sparsely populated but today containing about two-thirds of California's total population, would become the State of Colorado (the name ''Colorado'' was later adopted for [[Colorado Territory|another territory]] established in 1861), and the northern counties of [[Del Norte County|Del Norte]], [[Siskiyou County|Siskiyou]], [[Modoc County|Modoc]], [[Humboldt County, California|Humboldt]], [[Trinity County, California|Trinity]], [[Shasta County|Shasta]], [[Lassen County|Lassen]], [[Tehama County|Tehama]], [[Plumas County|Plumas]], and portions of [[Butte County, California|Butte]], [[Colusa County|Colusa]] (which included what is now [[Glenn County]]), and [[Mendocino County|Mendocino]], a region which today has a population of little more than half a million, would become the State of Shasta. The primary reason was the size of the state's territory. At the time, the representation in Congress was too small for such a large territory, it seemed too extensive for one government, and the state capital was too inaccessible because of the distances to Southern California and various other areas. The bill eventually died in the Senate as it became very low priority compared to other pressing political matters.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/>\n* In 1859, the legislature and governor approved the Pico Act (named after the bill's sponsor [[Andr\u00e9s Pico]], state senator from Southern California) splitting off the region south of the [[36th parallel north]] as the [[Territory of Colorado (California)|Territory of Colorado]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leo|first1=Michael Di|last2=Smith|first2=Eleanor|title=Two Californias: The Myths And Realities Of A State Divided Against Itself|date=June 1, 1983|publisher=Island Press|isbn=9780933280168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|language=en|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307001017/https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|archive-date=March 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=California|first1=Historical Society of Southern|last2=California|first2=Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern|title=The Quarterly|date=1901|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA230|accessdate=November 10, 2016|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628130547/http://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA230|archive-date=June 28, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sandefur|first1=Timothy|title=Hindsight|url=http://www.callawyer.com/story.cfm?eid=900573&evid=1|accessdate=November 10, 2016|work=Callawyer.com|date=April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006123653/http://www.callawyer.com/story.cfm?eid=900573&evid=1|archive-date=October 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The primary reason cited was the difference in both culture and geography between Northern and Southern California. It was signed by the [[Governor of California|State governor]] [[John B. Weller]], approved overwhelmingly by voters in the proposed ''Territory of Colorado'', and sent to [[Washington, D.C.]] with a strong advocate in Senator [[Milton Latham]].  However, the secession crisis and [[American Civil War]] following the election of Lincoln in 1860 prevented the proposal from ever coming to a vote.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Leo|first1=Michael Di|last2=Smith|first2=Eleanor|title=Two Californias: The Myths And Realities Of A State Divided Against Itself|publisher=Island Press|isbn=9780933280168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|language=en|pages=9\u201330|year=1983|access-date=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307001017/https://books.google.com/books?id=OEqiYRm-ohMC&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27|archive-date=March 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA223#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=J. M. Guinn, HOW CALIFORNIA ESCAPED STATE DIVISION, The Quarterly, Volumes 5-6 By Historical Society of Southern California, Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern California|accessdate=October 4, 2014|last1=California|first1=Historical Society of Southern|last2=California|first2=Los Angeles County Pioneers of Southern|year=1901|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207030747/http://books.google.com/books?id=WCMLAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA223#v=onepage&q=&f=false|archive-date=December 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcet.org/updaily/socal_focus/history/32239-how-southern-california-tried-to-split-from-the-north.html|title=Civil War: How Southern California Tried to Split from Northern California|work=KCET|accessdate=October 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120173650/http://www.kcet.org/updaily/socal_focus/history/32239-how-southern-california-tried-to-split-from-the-north.html|archive-date=November 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* In the late 19th century, there was serious talk in Sacramento of splitting the state in two at the [[Tehachapi Mountains]],{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} because of the difficulty of transportation across the rugged range. The discussion ended when it was determined that building a highway over the mountains was feasible; this road later became the [[Ridge Route]], which today is [[Interstate 5]] over [[Tejon Pass]].\n\n===20th century===\n* Since the mid-19th century, the mountainous region of northern California and parts of southwestern [[Oregon]] have been proposed as a separate state. In 1941, some counties in the area ceremonially seceded, one day a week, from their respective states as the [[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|State of Jefferson]]. This movement disappeared after America's entry into World War II, but the notion has been rekindled in recent years.<ref name=\"latimes-09-2013\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/25/local/la-me-ln-modoc-county-secession-20130925 |title=Modoc becomes second California county to back secession drive |date=September 25, 2013 |first=Lee |last=Romney |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413222754/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/25/local/la-me-ln-modoc-county-secession-20130925 |archive-date=April 13, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The [[California State Senate]] voted on June 4, 1965, to divide California into two states, with the [[Tehachapi Mountains]] as the boundary. Sponsored by State Senator [[Richard J. Dolwig]] (R-San Mateo), the resolution proposed to separate the 7 southern counties, with a majority of the state's population, from the 51 other counties, and passed 27\u201312. To be effective, the amendment would have needed approval by the State Assembly, by California voters, and by the United States Congress. As expected by Dolwig, the proposal did not get out of committee in the Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|title=California Senate acts to cut state in two in districting fight|work=Syracuse Herald-Journal|date=June 5, 1965|page=1}}</ref>\n* In 1992, [[California State Assembly|State Assemblyman]] [[Stan Statham]] sponsored a bill to allow a referendum in each county on a partition into three new states: North, Central, and South California. The proposal passed in the State Assembly but died in the [[California State Senate|State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=JIm|title=Upstate, downstate|url=http://www.newsreview.com/sacramento/Content?oid=10287|accessdate=July 7, 2008|work=Sacramento News & Review|date=January 3, 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128035359/http://www.newsreview.com/sacramento/content?oid=10287|archive-date=January 28, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n<gallery>\nFile:CaliFOURnia map.svg|2003: Martin Hutchinson's proposal{{legend|#c4820e|San Diego / Orange County / [[Inland Empire]]}}{{legend|#003262|Greater Los Angeles}}{{legend|#fdb515|San Francisco / Sacramento/ Santa Cruz / Silicon Valley}}{{legend|#3b7ea1|Northern / Central Valley}}\nFile:Map of California highlighting 2009 Maze CoastWest.svg|2009: [[Bill Maze]]'s proposal{{legend|#008000|[[Coastal California|Coastal or Western California]]}}\nFile:South California proposal (vector).svg|2011: Jeff Stone's proposal{{legend|#f00|South California}}\nFile:Six Californias.svg|2013: Map of the [[Six Californias]]{{legend|#800000|Jefferson}}{{legend|#808000|North California}}{{legend|#008000|Silicon Valley}}{{legend|#008080|Central California}}{{legend|#000080|West California}}{{legend|#800080|South California}}\nFile:New_California_map.svg|2018: Paul Preston's proposal{{legend|#0055d4|New California}}\nFile:Cal3 map.svg|2018: Map of [[Cal 3]]{{legend|#00aae7|Northern California}}{{legend|#00468b|California}}{{legend|#9ac6ea|Southern California}}\n</gallery>\n\n* In the wake of the [[California gubernatorial recall election, 2003|2003 gubernatorial recall]], Tim Holt and Martin Hutchinson proposed in separate newspaper [[op-ed]]s that the state should split into as many as four new states, dividing distinct geographically and politically defined regions as the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], [[North Coast, California|North Coast]], and [[California Central Valley|Central Valley]], as well as the historic [[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|Shasta/Jefferson]] region, into their own states.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2003/08/17/IN81189.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=A modest proposal: downsize California! | first=Tim | last=Holt | date=August 17, 2003 | access-date=August 8, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309152540/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2003%2F08%2F17%2FIN81189.DTL | archive-date=March 9, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Reuters-Hutchinson>{{cite news|last=Hutchinson|first=Martin|title=Califournia Breakup?|url=http://www.breakingviews.com/2009/05/21/California%20break-up.aspx?sg=features|accessdate=February 23, 2011|newspaper=Thomas Reuters|date=May 21, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708092300/http://www.breakingviews.com/2009/05/21/California%20break-up.aspx?sg=features|archivedate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> \n* In early 2009, former State Assemblyman [[Bill Maze]] began lobbying to split thirteen coastal counties, which usually vote Democratic, into a separate state to be known as either \"[[Coastal California]]\" or \"Western California\". Maze's primary reason for wanting to split the state was because of how \"conservatives don't have a voice\" and how Los Angeles and San Francisco \"control the state\". The counties that would make up the new state would be [[Marin County, California|Marin]], [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa]], [[Alameda County, California|Alameda]], [[San Francisco County, California|San Francisco]], [[San Mateo County, California|San Mateo]], [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]], [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz]], [[San Benito County, California|San Benito]], [[Monterey County, California|Monterey]], [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]], [[Santa Barbara County, California|Santa Barbara]], [[Ventura County, California|Ventura]], and [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles]] Counties. It has also been proposed that the state be split in two simply at the straight divide of the [[120th meridian west]], much like its border with the state of [[Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downsizeca.org/|title=Home Page|date=October 23, 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023221939/http://www.downsizeca.org/|archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref>\n* In June 2011, Republican Riverside County Supervisor Jeff Stone called for Riverside, Imperial, San Diego, Orange, San Bernardino, Kings, Kern, Fresno, Tulare, Inyo, Madera, Mariposa and Mono counties (see map, highlighted in red) to separate from California to form the new state of ''South California''. Officials in Sacramento responded derisively, with governor [[Jerry Brown]]'s spokesperson saying \"A secessionist movement? What is this, [[American Civil War|1860]]? It's a supremely ridiculous waste of everybody's time.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8630830/Could-South-California-become-the-51st-US-state.html|title=Could 'South California' become the 51st US state?|publisher=[[Daily Telegraph]]|date=July 11, 2011|access-date=April 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510172347/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8630830/Could-South-California-become-the-51st-US-state.html|archive-date=May 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and fellow supervisor Bob Buster calling Stone \"crazy\", suggesting \"Stone has gotten too much sun recently.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Official Calls For Riverside, 12 Other Counties To Secede From California|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/01/official-calls-for-riverside-12-other-counties-to-secede-from-california/|date=July 1, 2011|work=KCBS|access-date=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716171509/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/01/official-calls-for-riverside-12-other-counties-to-secede-from-california/|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In September 2013, county supervisors in both Siskiyou County and Modoc County voted to join a bid to separate and create a new \"[[Jefferson (proposed Pacific state)|State of Jefferson]]\".<ref name=\"latimes-09-2013\"/>  Mark Baird, spokesperson for the Jefferson Declaration Committee, is reported to have said the group hopes to obtain commitments from as many as a dozen counties, after which they will ask the state legislature to permit formation of the new state based on Article 4, Section 3 of the US Constitution.  In January 2014, supervisors in [[Glenn County, California|Glenn County]] voted in favor of separation,<ref name=\"latimes-01-2014\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-glenn-county-backs-breakaway-state-20140123-story.html |title=Glenn County is third in Calif. to back breakaway State of Jefferson |date=January 23, 2014 |first=Lee |last=Romney |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623224044/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-glenn-county-backs-breakaway-state-20140123-story.html |archive-date=June 23, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in April 2014, [[Yuba County, California|Yuba County]] supervisors voted to become the fourth California county to join the movement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/04/16/yuba-county-joins-state-of-jefferson-movement-to-split-california/ |title=Yuba County Joins State Of Jefferson Movement To Split California |date=April 16, 2014 |first=Nick |last=Janes |publisher=CBS13 Sacramento |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626223758/http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/04/16/yuba-county-joins-state-of-jefferson-movement-to-split-california/ |archive-date=June 26, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On June 3, 2014, residents in [[Del Norte County, California|Del Norte County]] voted against separation by 58 percent to 42 percent,<ref>[http://elections.co.del-norte.ca.us/elections/june-3-2014-primary-election June 3, 2014 Primary Election - County of Del Norte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608033400/http://elections.co.del-norte.ca.us/elections/june-3-2014-primary-election |date=June 8, 2014 }};</ref> however, voters in [[Tehama County, California|Tehama County]] supported a separation initiative by 57 percent to 43 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/06/04/one-california-county-votes-to-secede-two-counties-vote-to-stick-around/ |title=One California county votes to separate, two counties vote to stick around |date=June 4, 2014 |first=Reid |last=Wilson |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715234933/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/06/04/one-california-county-votes-to-secede-two-counties-vote-to-stick-around/ |archive-date=July 15, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On July 22, 2014, Sutter County voted 5-0 to join the State of Jefferson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.co.sutter.ca.us/apps/agendas/file.aspx?agenda=5717 |title=Sutter County Board of Supervisors Summary of July 22, 2014 |date=July 22, 2014 |first=Steven |last=Smith |publisher=Sutter County |accessdate=July 22, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801095615/https://www.co.sutter.ca.us/apps/agendas/file.aspx?agenda=5717 |archive-date=August 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Six Californias]]: On December 19, 2013, venture capitalist [[Timothy C. Draper|Tim Draper]] submitted a six-page proposal<ref>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Six Californias|url=https://www.scribd.com/embeds/192645393/content|work=Initiative Measure Submitted Directly to Voters|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803170347/https://www.scribd.com/embeds/192645393/content|archive-date=August 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=six-californias>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Six Californias|url=http://www.sixcalifornias.info/|work=Website|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220111359/http://www.sixcalifornias.info/|archive-date=December 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  to the California Attorney General to split California into six new states, citing improved representation, governance, and competition between industries.<ref name=draper-six-californias>{{cite web|last=Draper|first=Timothy|title=Tim Draper Wants To Split California Into Pieces And Turn Silicon Valley Into Its Own State|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/19/tim-draper-six-californias-secede-silicon-valley-ballot-initiative/|publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=December 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220073434/http://techcrunch.com/2013/12/19/tim-draper-six-californias-secede-silicon-valley-ballot-initiative/|archive-date=December 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  On February 19, 2014, [[Secretary of State of California|Secretary of State]] [[Debra Bowen]] approved the proposal allowing supporters to start collecting signatures in order to qualify the petition for a ballot. A total of 807,615 registered voters were needed by July 18, 2014 for the proposal to appear on the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fields|first=Kayle|title=Petition to Split California Into Six States Gets Green Light|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/02/petition-to-split-california-into-six-states-gets-green-light/|work=abcnews.go.com|accessdate=February 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221072359/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/02/petition-to-split-california-into-six-states-gets-green-light/|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 14, the petition organizer announced that the proposal received enough signatures to be placed on the ballot in two years,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chaussee|first1=Jennifer|title=Billionaire's breakup plan would chop California into six states|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-california-breakup-20140714,0,4830203.story|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=Chicago Tribune|agency=Reuter|date=July 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720001146/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-california-breakup-20140714,0,4830203.story|archive-date=July 20, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> however, it was determined that only about two thirds were valid and the petition fell short of qualifying for the November 2016 ballot.<ref>[http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/12/6702457/six-californias-initiative-fails.html Six Californias initiative fails] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927092523/http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/12/6702457/six-californias-initiative-fails.html |date=September 27, 2014 }}, sacbee.com.</ref>\n* New California: On January 16, 2018, the 501(c)(4) organization New California, organized by conservative radio talk show host Paul Preston, published its proposed state's Declaration of Independence. As motivation for the split, they cited that California ranked 48th out of 50 states for business climate and also cited high taxes and California's failure to follow the state and federal constitutions. New California would include the rural counties that make up most of the state's area, leaving the more heavily populated areas around San Francisco, Sacramento, and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite web|url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/01/15/new-california-declares-independence-from-rest-of-state/|title=New California Declares Independence From Rest Of State|date=January 15, 2018|website=cbslocal.com|access-date=January 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123184710/http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/01/15/new-california-declares-independence-from-rest-of-state/|archive-date=January 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> New California would also include the urban areas of [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa County]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], and [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]], bringing the population to around 20 million.<ref name=\"cbs\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Betz|first1=Bradford|title='New California' movement seeks to divide the Golden State in half|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/17/new-california-movement-seeks-to-divide-golden-state-in-half.html|accessdate=January 19, 2018|work=Fox News|date=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119084748/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/17/new-california-movement-seeks-to-divide-golden-state-in-half.html|archive-date=January 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In April 2018, the [[Cal 3]] organization announced it had more than 600,000 signatures to place an initiative on the November 2018 ballot proposing that California should be split into three separate states.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://threestateca.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Press-Release-041118.pdf |title=\"CAL 3\" Initiative to Partition California Reaches Unprecedented Milestone |date=April 11, 2018 |publisher=Cal 3 |accessdate=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414041639/https://threestateca.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Press-Release-041118.pdf |archive-date=April 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The signatures must be verified before the proposal qualifies for the ballot<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/split-California-3-states-Northern-Southern-12830724.php|title=Plan to split California into 3 states may qualify for ballot|last1=Ting|first1=Eric|date=April 13, 2018|website=SFGate|publisher=Hearst|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419072319/https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/split-California-3-states-Northern-Southern-12830724.php|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> - this was achieved by June 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/proposal-split-california-three-states-earns-spot-november-ballot-n882646 |title=Proposal to split California into three states earns spot on November ballot |last=Helsel |first=Phil |date=June 13, 2018 |website=nbcnews.com |publisher=NBC News |access-date=June 13, 2018 |quote=Voters in the massive state of California, touted as having an economy larger than most countries, could decide whether to support a plan calling for The Golden State to be split into three. An initiative that would direct the governor to seek Congressional approval to divide California into three states has enough valid signatures to be eligible for the Nov. 6 ballot, the Secretary of State\u2019s office said Tuesday. If the initiative is not withdrawn, it will be qualified for the ballot on June 28. Even if approved by voters, it faces the hurdle of approval by Congress. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613130540/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/proposal-split-california-three-states-earns-spot-november-ballot-n882646 |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2018, the [[California Supreme Court]] pulled the Cal 3 proposal from the ballot for further state constitutional review.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Splitting-up-Calif-State-Supreme-Court-takes-13085880.php | title=Splitting up California: State Supreme Court takes initiative off ballot | first=Bob | last=Egelko | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | date=July 18, 2018 | quote=[T]he court issued a unanimous order removing the measure from the ballot and ordering further legal arguments on whether it should be placed on another ballot in 2020 or struck down altogether | access-date=July 19, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719100248/https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Splitting-up-Calif-State-Supreme-Court-takes-13085880.php | archive-date=July 19, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2020, \"Move Oregon's Border For a Greater Idaho\" proposed breaking off most of Oregon's area and some of Northern California and join it with Idaho. The areas proposed to break off of Oregon and California vote Republican but in a state whose legislatures are dominated by Democrats. Douglas and Josephine counties in Oregon approved language for petitions to put a measure on the ballot. Even if passed by voters, it would still need approval from all three state legislatures.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/02/24/808916891/some-oregonians-want-to-leave-and-take-part-of-the-state-to-idaho-with-them | title=Some Oregonians Want To Leave And Take Part Of The State To Idaho With Them| work=[[NPR]]| location=Washington, D.C.| date=February 24, 2020| accessdate=February 26, 2020|}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pacific-northwest-news/2020/02/ballot-initiative-effort-to-move-eastern-oregon-counties-to-idaho-gains-momentum-leader-calls-it-peaceful-revolution.html | title=Ballot-initiative effort to move eastern Oregon counties to Idaho gains momentum; leader calls it \u2018peaceful revolution\u2019| work=[[The Oregonian]]| location= Portland, Oregon | date=February 17, 2020| accessdate=February 26, 2020|}}</ref>\n\n==Secession==\n\n===Ecotopia===\nWriter [[Ernest Callenbach]] wrote a 1975 novel, entitled ''[[Ecotopia]]'', in which he proposed a full-blown secession of Northern California, Oregon, and Washington from the United States in order to focus upon environmentally friendly living and culture. He later abandoned the idea stating: \"We are now fatally interconnected, in climate change, ocean impoverishment, agricultural soil loss, etc. etc. etc.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/san-francisco-secession-ecotopia_n_898457.html|title = San Francisco Secession: Could It Create 'Ecotopia'?|author = Matt Sledge|newspaper = Huffington Post|date = July 14, 2011|access-date = July 15, 2011|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110717235335/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/san-francisco-secession-ecotopia_n_898457.html|archive-date = July 17, 2011|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===Cascadia===\n{{main article|Cascadia (independence movement)}}\nWhile mostly consisting of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[Oregon]], [[Idaho]] and [[British Columbia]] in Canada, proposals for an independent Cascadia often include portions of northern California.\n\n===Calexit===\n{{main article|Yes California}}\nIn the wake of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Donald Trump]]'s winning the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], a fringe movement organized by [[Yes California]], referred to as \"Calexit\" - a term inspired by the successful 2016 [[Brexit]] referendum, arose in a bid to gather the 585,407 signatures necessary to place a [[secession]]ist question on the 2018 ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/%E2%80%98california-is-a-nation-not-a-state%E2%80%99-a-fringe-movement-wants-a-break-from-the-us/ar-AAn5LLx?OCID=ansmsnnews11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220093900/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/%E2%80%98california-is-a-nation-not-a-state%E2%80%99-a-fringe-movement-wants-a-break-from-the-us/ar-AAn5LLx?OCID=ansmsnnews11 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 20, 2017 |date=February 20, 2017 |title=\u2018California is a nation, not a state\u2019: A fringe movement wants a break from the U.S. |work=MSNBC}}</ref> In July 2018, the objectives of the Calexit initiative were expanded upon by including a plan to carve out an \u201cautonomous Native American nation\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.stanforddaily.com/2018/09/27/final-hf-calexit-supporters-relaunch-campaign-with-proposals-to-create-a-north-american-nation/|title=Calexit supporters relaunch campaign with proposals to create Native American nation|date=September 27, 2018|work=The Stanford Daily|access-date=November 11, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110220146/https://www.stanforddaily.com/2018/09/27/final-hf-calexit-supporters-relaunch-campaign-with-proposals-to-create-a-north-american-nation/|archive-date=November 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> that would take up the eastern part of California, and \"postponing its ballot referendum approach in favor of convincing Republican states to support their breakaway efforts.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n====California National Party====\nFounded in 2015, California National Party (CNP) is a political party advocating a pragmatic platform. The CNP also seeks, as a long-term goal, the secession of California from the United States by legal and peaceful means.\n\nThe California National Party draws its inspiration from the [[Scottish National Party]], which advocates for the independence of Scotland from the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=California could see new political party with independence goal|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article54004530.html|work=Sacramento Bee|accessdate=March 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308223549/http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article54004530.html|archive-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-californians-inspired-by-scotland-to-pursue-independent-nationhood|title=Meet the California Separatists Leading a New Movement to Secede from the United States|website=VICE|language=en-us|access-date=March 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401202254/http://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-californians-inspired-by-scotland-to-pursue-independent-nationhood|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2016, the California Secretary of State's office sent a memorandum to each of California's 58 county Registration of Voters offices to inform them that they had \"received formal notification from the California National Party of their intent to qualify\" as a political party on December 7, 2015, and thereafter assigned the party a code designation of \"CNP\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ccrov/pdf/2016/january/16013ms.pdf|title=California Secretary of State {{!}} Political Body: California National Party|date=January 6, 2016|access-date=March 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215091539/http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov//ccrov/pdf/2016/january/16013ms.pdf|archive-date=February 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFormal organizing for the party did not begin until June 2016, when the CNP held its first convention and elections in Sacramento, California.  At that convention, Theo Slater and Andria Franco were elected as Chair and Vice Chair. Jed Wheeler, founder of Californians for Independence, was elected Secretary as the two groups merged. The CNP adopted a new platform, based on the Californians for Independence platform, in September of that year;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californianational.party/en_US/platform-california-national-party/#peace-and-defense|title=The California National Party Platform - California National Party|website=californianational.party|language=en-US|access-date=March 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328195126/https://californianational.party/en_US/platform-california-national-party/#peace-and-defense|archive-date=March 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and launched a website, mailing list, and recruitment drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ror/ror-odd-year-2019/nonqual.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323230018/https://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/ror/ror-odd-year-2019/nonqual.pdf |archive-date=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The party re-filed with the Secretary of State in November 2016 and the new leadership was officially recognized<ref name=\":3\" /> shortly after.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of U.S. state partition proposals]]\n* [[Secession in New York]]\n* [[Texas divisionism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed states of the United States|California]]\n[[Category:Separatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Politics of California]]\n[[Category:History of California]]\n", "name_user": "Mhhossein", "label": "safe",