793e}}\n\n{{coord missing|Gansu}}\n\n[[Category:Gansu]]\n[[Category:Historical Turkic states]]\n[[Category:Nomadic groups in Eurasia]]\n[[Category:Uyghurs]]\n[[Category:Uyghur Khaganate]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Chinese history]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Ganzhou Uyghur Kingdom\n|common_name  = Ganzhou Uyghur Kingdom\n|status       = Kingdom\n|government_type = Monarchy\n|capital      = Gan Prefecture ([[Zhangye]])\n|common_languages = [[Old Uyghur language]]<br />[[Middle Chinese]]\n|religion     = [[Manichaeism]]<br/>[[Buddhism]]\n|year_start   = 894\n|year_end     = 1036\n|p1           = Uyghur Khaganate \n|s1           = Dingnan Jiedushi\n|image_map    = Guiyi Circuit.png\n|image_flag   =\n|title_leader = Idiqut\n|stat_year1   = \n|stat_area1   = \n|today        = [[China]]\n}}\n{{History of the Turkic peoples}}\nThe '''Ganzhou Uyghur Kingdom (\u7518\u5dde\u56de\u9dbb)''', also referred to as the Hexi [[Uyghurs]], was established in 894 around [[Zhangye|Gan Prefecture]] in modern [[Zhangye]].{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=47}}{{sfn|Millward|2007|p=46}} The kingdom lasted from 894 to 1036; during that time, many of Ganzhou's residents converted to [[Buddhism]].{{sfn|Bosworth|2000|p=70}}\n\nThe [[Hexi Corridor]], located within modern [[Gansu]], was traditionally a Chinese inroad into [[Central Asia]]. From the 9th to 11th centuries this area was shared between the Ganzhou Uyghurs and the [[Guiyi Circuit]]. By the early 11th century both the Uyghurs and Guiyi Circuit were conquered by the [[Tangut people]] of the [[Western Xia|Western Xia dynasty]].<ref name=\"Bell\">{{cite book|last=Bell|first=Connor Joseph|title=The Uyghur Transformation in Medieval Inner Asia: From Nomadic Turkic Tradition to Cultured Mongol Administrators|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d3tNUcYj32QC&pg=PA65|accessdate=21 December |year=2008|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=9780549807957|pages=65\u201369}}</ref>\n\nThe Ganzhou Uyghur rulers were descended from the [[Yaglakar clan|House of Yaglakar]].\n\n==History==\n\nThere was a pre-existing community of Uyghurs at Gan Prefecture by 840 at the very latest.\n\nAround the years 881 and 882, Gan Prefecture slipped from the control of the Guiyi Circuit.\n\nIn 894 the Uyghurs established the Ganzhou Uyghur Kingdom in Gan Prefecture.\n\nIn 910 the Ganzhou Uyghurs attacked the Kingdom of Jinshan (Guiyi).\n\nIn 911 the Ganzhou Uyghurs attacked the Kingdom of Jinshan and forced them into an alliance as a lesser partner.\n\nIn 916 a Ganzhou Uyghur princess was married to Cao Yijin, governor of the Guiyi Circuit.\n\nIn 920 Huaijian Khagan became sickly.\n\nIn 924 Huaijian Khagan died and his sons Diyin and Renmei fought over the throne with Diyin coming out on top.\n\nIn 925 Cao Yijin led an attack on the Ganzhou Uyghurs and defeated them.\n\nIn 926 Diyin died and Aduoyu succeeded him as Shunhua Khagan. Shunhua Khagan married Cao Yijin's daughter.\n\nIn 930 Cao Yijin visited the Ganzhou Uyghur court in Gan Prefecture.\n\nIn 933 Shunhua Khagan died and Jingqiong succeeded him.\n\nIn 961 the Ganzhou Uyghurs accepted the [[Song dynasty]] as suzerains.<ref name=\"knowledge\">http://www.chinaknowledge.de/History/Altera/uighurs.html</ref>\n\nIn 975 Jingqiong died and Yeluohe Mili'e succeeded him.\n\nIn 983 Jingqiong died and Lusheng succeeded him.\n\nIn 1003 Lusheng died and Zhongshun Baode Khagan succeeded him. The [[Tanguts]] attacked the Ganzhou Uyghurs but were defeated.\n\nIn 1008 the Ganzhou Uyghurs and Tanguts engaged in combat and the Uyghurs emerged victorious. The [[Liao dynasty]] attacked the Ganzhou Uyghurs and defeated them.\n\nIn 1009 the Ganzhou Uyghurs captured [[Wuwei, Gansu|Liang]] Prefecture.\n\nIn 1010 the Liao dynasty attacked the Ganzhou Uyghurs and defeated them.\n\nIn 1016 Zhongshun Baode Khagan died and Huaining Shunhua Khagan succeeded him.\n\nIn 1023 Huaining Shunhua Khagan died and Guizhong Baoshun Khagan succeeded him.\n\nIn 1026 the Ganzhou Uyghurs were defeated in battle by the Liao dynasty.\n\nIn 1028 the Ganhzhou Uyghurs were defeated by the Tanguts. Guizhong Baoshun Khagan died and Baoguo Khagan succeeded him.\n\nIn 1036 the Ganzhou Uyghur Kingdom was annexed by the Tanguts. After the destruction of their realm, the Ganzhou Uyghurs migrated west and settled between [[Dunhuang]] and the [[Qaidam Basin]], where they came be known as the Yellow Head Uyghurs. They practiced Buddhism and lived as pastoral nomads. Their descendants are today known as the [[Yugurs]].\n\n==Modern era==\nThe modern day descendants of the Ganzhou Uyghurs are known as the [[Yugur]].<ref>''Manichaeism and Nestorian Christianity'', H. J. Klimkeit, '''History of Civilizations of Central Asia''', Vol.4, Part 2,  70</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Turkic peoples]]\n*[[Timeline of the Turkic peoples (500\u20131300) ]]\n*[[List of Turkic dynasties and countries]]\n*[[Uyghur Khaganate]]\n*[[Qocho]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Fu-Hs\u00fceh, Yang. 1994. \u201cOn the Sha-chou Uighur Kingdom\u201d. Central Asiatic Journal 38 (1). Harrassowitz Verlag: 80\u2013107. https://www.jstor.org/stable/41929460.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation|last=Asimov|first=M.S.|year=1998|title=History of civilizations of Central Asia Volume IV The age of achievement: A.D. 750 to the end of the fifteenth century Part One The historical, social and economic setting|publisher=UNESCO Publishing}}\n*{{citation|last=Barfield|first=Thomas|title=The Perilous Frontier: Nomadic Empires and China|year=1989|publisher=Basil Blackwell}}\n*{{citation|last=Benson|first=Linda|title=China's last Nomads: the history and culture of China's Kazaks|year=1998|publisher=M.E. Sharpe}}\n*{{citation|last=Bregel|first=Yuri|year=2003|title=An Historical Atlas of Central Asia|publisher=Brill}}\n*{{citation|last=Bosworth|first=Clifford Edmund|title=\tThe Age of Achievement: A.D. 750 to the End of the Fifteenth Century - Vol. 4, Part II : The Achievements (History of Civilizations of Central Asia)|year=2000|pub