{"title_page": "John Finlay Duff", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:John Finlay Duff.jpeg|thumb|right]]\n\n'''John Finlay Duff''' (1 April 1799 \u2013 18 May 1868)<ref>Newspaper obituaries gave his age as 73. Either this was an error, or he was born around 1794.</ref> was a ship's captain and businessman in the Colony of South Australia.\n\n==History==\nDuff was born in [[Dundee]], Scotland in 1799, son of John Duff and his wife Elisabeth, n\u00e9e Finlay, of a ship owning family. He qualified as a master mariner and first reached Australia in July 1835, when he captained the ''[[Africaine (1832 ship)|Africaine]]'' from London to [[Hobart, Tasmania|Hobart]].\n\nOn his next voyage to Australia, the barque ''Africaine'' left [[London Docks]] on 28 June, but without Captain Duff, who was to be married the next day at [[St Botolph's Aldgate]]. The newlyweds joined the ship, anchored in [[The Downs (ship anchorage)|The Downs]] off [[Deal, Kent]], on the following day. Witness to the wedding was his friend and business partner [[John Hallett (South Australian politician)|John Hallett]], who with his family were among the ''Africaine'' migrants.<ref name=brummitt>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~barqueasia1839/FINLAYDUFF.htm|author=Jane Brummitt|title=John Finlay Duff, Anne Eliza Duff, and their daughter Jessie Light Duff|publisher=ancestry.com|accessdate=24 May 2005}}</ref>\nThe ship, which had been chartered by [[Robert Gouger]] and [[John Brown (colonist)|John Brown]] with around 60 emigrants and a considerable cargo bound for South Australia on what has been dubbed the \"[[First Fleet of South Australia]]\", had an uneventful voyage and on 1 November 1836 were off the coast of [[Kangaroo Island]], near [[Cape Borda]]. \n:A small party asked to be put ashore, intending to hike along the north of the island to Nepean Bay, but they found the going much more difficult than Sutherland's 1819 memoir led them to expect,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191550511 |title=Early History of K.I. |newspaper=[[The Kangaroo Island Courier]] |location=Kingscote, SA |date=11 December 1926 |accessdate=9 June 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> with little food and water to be had. Mr. Osborne took ill and could proceed no further; Dr. Slater stayed with him, and both presumably perished, though if found, their bodies were never identified. Ten days after they set foot on the island the remainder, Nantes, Warren, Bagg and Fisher, reached the settlement at [[Kingscote, South Australia|Kingscote]], where they were hospitably received by [[Samuel Stephens (Colonial Manager)|Samuel Stephens]] and [[Edward Wright (medical doctor)|Dr. Wright]], other employees of the [[South Australian Company]] and fellow-passenger John Hallett, who had been searching for them the better part of the previous week.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59745849 |title=History of Kangaroo Island |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=12 September 1914 |accessdate=25 May 2015 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Finding their ship gone, at least one of the exploration party, Robert Fisher, was critical of Duff for not waiting longer for them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31749656 |title=South Australian Company |newspaper=[[South Australian Gazette and Colonial Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=8 July 1837 |accessdate=25 May 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \nThe ''Africaine'' left for the mainland on 6 November, Duff having decided not to wait any longer, encountered William Light's brig ''Rapid'' at [[Rapid Bay, South Australia|Rapid Bay]], and Light was welcomed aboard the ''Africaine'', then moved on to [[Holdfast Bay]], arriving before the {{HMS|Buffalo|1813|2}}. Duff was immediately commissioned to set sail for Hobart for urgently needed supplies, incidentally making useful business contacts in Van Diemen's Land.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\nDuff and Hallett, who were both part-owners of the ''Africaine'' with Thomas Finlay (perhaps Duff's maternal grandfather),<ref name=bound>{{cite web|url=http://boundforsouthaustralia.net.au/journey-content/captain-john-finlay-duff.html|title=Bound for South Australia: John Finlay Duff|publisher=History SA and the Department of Education and Children's Services|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> opened a store and shipping agency on [[Grenfell Street, Adelaide|Grenfell Street]] in 1837, one of the first in the Colony. Their residences were both on [[South Terrace, Adelaide]], almost adjacent; Duff moved from South Terrace around the end of 1846.\n\nThey dissolved their partnership in December 1840. Both had substantial land holdings; Duff purchased one of the original town acres at the corner of Currie Street and West Terrace and larger properties near the city.<ref name=brummitt/> He allowed his farmer tenants to pay their rent in bags of wheat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71618540 |title=Local News |newspaper=[[Southern Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=24 November 1843 |accessdate=26 May 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He donated part of his property \"Woodford\", near [[Magill, South Australia|Magill]], for St. George's Anglican Church. They had other properties further out: at Port Lincoln, and \"Woodford\" on the [[South Para River|Para River]], where he ran sheep. In 1837 he exported in four bales of wool to England \u2013 the first from South Australia. Duff and Hallett were early and generous contributors to the establishment of [[Holy Trinity Church, Adelaide|Trinity Church]].<ref name=brummitt/> \n \nIn 1838 Duff and his wife returned to England where their first child was born, and was christened at the church where they had been married (she was to be christened a second time, as Jessie Light Duff at Trinity Church, North Terrace, Adelaide, in honour of Colonel William Light). They returned to South Australia as fellow-passengers on the ''Asia'' with Dr. [[George Mayo]], with whom he developed a long-lasting friendship, arriving in July 1839.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\nDuff owned the [[schooner]] ''Waterwitch'', usually commanded by D. Talbert, which traded between [[Mauritius]], [[R\u00e9union|Bourbon]] and [[Port Adelaide]], also between Port Adelaide and [[Fremantle, Western Australia]]. She was lost with all hands on a return voyage which left Mauritius on 28 August September 1846. He also owned the [[barque]] ''Guiana'', which he took to Mauritius twice, and the ''Augustus'' which he also commanded on several Mauritius voyages.\n\nIn 1859, Captain Duff accepted the appointment of Harbourmaster and Lightkeeper at Glenelg, which he held for several years. One of his first duties was to decide on the suitability of [[Cape Willoughby]] for a lighthouse.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50247597 |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 June 1849 |accessdate=26 May 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nHe died at his home at [[Glenelg, South Australia|New Glenelg]], and was buried at [[West Terrace Cemetery]]. Robert Gouger thought very highly of him, noting that \"\u2026 he appears to be a thorough sailor, decisive and skilful; he pays equal attention to all his passengers, has no favorites apparently, and therefore is a general favorite.\"<ref name=bound/> Light was also fulsome in his praise for Duff's seamanship and judgment.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=5 |The Duff SA Voyages\n|-\n!Ship\n!Departure\n!Port\n!Arrival\n!Notes\n|-\n||{{ship||Africaine|ship|2}} || ||London||6 November 1836 || part of the [[First Fleet of South Australia]]\n|-\n||''Africaine'' || ||Hobart||30 January 1837 ||\n|-\n||''Africaine'' || ||Launceston||14 July 1837 ||\n|-\n||''Sir Charles McCarthy'' || ||Launceston ||8 October 1837 || wrecked at Glenelg November 1837\n|-\n||''Asia'' || ||London ||16 July 1839 ||\n|-\n||''Waterwitch'' ||3 March 1840 ||Launceston || ||\n|-\n||''Guiana'' || ||Mauritius||27 July 1842 || first cargo landed at the new port\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||21 March 1844 ||Sydney||16 June 1844 || misreported as bound for Mauritius\n|-\n||''Guiana'' ||16 August 1844 ||Mauritius ||8 February 1845 ||\n|-\n||''Guiana'' || ||Hobart ||4 April 1846 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||5 February 1847 ||Mauritius ||26 June 1847 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||13 July 1847 ||Hobart ||16 September 1847 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' || ||Mauritius ||13 July 1848 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' || ||Hobart ||23 November 1848 ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Family==\nDuff married Anna? Anne? Eliza Turner ( \u2013 22 November 1854) on 29 June 1836. Their children included:\n*Jessie Light Duff (29 November 1838 \u2013 ) married William S. Miller of Parkside on 4 September 1861\n<!-- Charles Reginald 1840\u20131841 -->\n*John Finlay Duff, Jr.(4 December 1843 \u2013 October 1897)<!--married A. S. Duff--> lived at Glenelg. He died at Argyle Downs Station. W.A.\n<!--*son 3 October 1845\u2013 -->\n*Eliza Dixon Duff (c. 1848 \u2013 18 August 1921) married John W. Stafford ( \u2013 ) on 13 May 1871\n\nHe married again, to Mary Schroder ( \u2013 ) on 24 April 1862. He died six years later. Their children included:\n\n*Joseph Stilling Duff (1863 \u2013 21 January 1920) married Adelaide Lurina Capper in 1886. He was a theatre manager and accountant, died in [[Wellington, New Zealand]].\n*Stuart Duncan Duff (1866 \u2013 17 June 1941) married Mabel Annie Shephard on 6 April 1898, lived at Marion, then Brighton.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duff, John Finlay}}\n[[Category:Australian ship owners]]\n[[Category:Australian sailors]]\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at West Terrace Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:John Finlay Duff.jpeg|thumb|right]]\n\n'''John Finlay Duff''' (1 April 1799 \u2013 18 May 1868)<ref>Newspaper obituaries gave his age as 73. Either this was an error, or he was born around 1794.</ref> was a ship's captain and businessman in the Colony of South Australia.\n\n==History==\nDuff was born in [[Dundee]], Scotland in 1799, son of John Duff and his wife Elisabeth, n\u00e9e Finlay, of a ship owning family. He qualified as a master mariner and first reached Australia in July 1835, when he captained the ''[[Africaine (1832 ship)|Africaine]]'' from London to [[Hobart, Tasmania|Hobart]].\n\nOn his next voyage to Australia, the barque ''Africaine'' left [[London Docks]] on 28 June, but without Captain Duff, who was to be married the next day at [[St Botolph's Aldgate]]. The newlyweds joined the ship, anchored in [[The Downs (ship anchorage)|The Downs]] off [[Deal, Kent]], on the following day. Witness to the wedding was his friend and business partner [[John Hallett (South Australian politician)|John Hallett]], who with his family were among the ''Africaine'' migrants.<ref name=brummitt>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~barqueasia1839/FINLAYDUFF.htm|author=Jane Brummitt|title=John Finlay Duff, Anne Eliza Duff, and their daughter Jessie Light Duff|publisher=ancestry.com|accessdate=24 May 2005}}</ref>\nThe ship, which had been chartered by [[Robert Gouger]] and John Brown with around 60 emigrants and a considerable cargo bound for South Australia on what has been dubbed the \"[[First Fleet of South Australia]]\", had an uneventful voyage and on 1 November 1836 were off the coast of [[Kangaroo Island]], near [[Cape Borda]]. \n:A small party asked to be put ashore, intending to hike along the north of the island to Nepean Bay, but they found the going much more difficult than Sutherland's 1819 memoir led them to expect,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191550511 |title=Early History of K.I. |newspaper=[[The Kangaroo Island Courier]] |location=Kingscote, SA |date=11 December 1926 |accessdate=9 June 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> with little food and water to be had. Mr. Osborne took ill and could proceed no further; Dr. Slater stayed with him, and both presumably perished, though if found, their bodies were never identified. Ten days after they set foot on the island the remainder, Nantes, Warren, Bagg and Fisher, reached the settlement at [[Kingscote, South Australia|Kingscote]], where they were hospitably received by [[Samuel Stephens (Colonial Manager)|Samuel Stephens]] and [[Edward Wright (medical doctor)|Dr. Wright]], other employees of the [[South Australian Company]] and fellow-passenger John Hallett, who had been searching for them the better part of the previous week.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59745849 |title=History of Kangaroo Island |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=12 September 1914 |accessdate=25 May 2015 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Finding their ship gone, at least one of the exploration party, Robert Fisher, was critical of Duff for not waiting longer for them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31749656 |title=South Australian Company |newspaper=[[South Australian Gazette and Colonial Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=8 July 1837 |accessdate=25 May 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \nThe ''Africaine'' left for the mainland on 6 November, Duff having decided not to wait any longer, encountered William Light's brig ''Rapid'' at [[Rapid Bay, South Australia|Rapid Bay]], and Light was welcomed aboard the ''Africaine'', then moved on to [[Holdfast Bay]], arriving before the {{HMS|Buffalo|1813|2}}. Duff was immediately commissioned to set sail for Hobart for urgently needed supplies, incidentally making useful business contacts in Van Diemen's Land.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\nDuff and Hallett, who were both part-owners of the ''Africaine'' with Thomas Finlay (perhaps Duff's maternal grandfather),<ref name=bound>{{cite web|url=http://boundforsouthaustralia.net.au/journey-content/captain-john-finlay-duff.html|title=Bound for South Australia: John Finlay Duff|publisher=History SA and the Department of Education and Children's Services|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> opened a store and shipping agency on [[Grenfell Street, Adelaide|Grenfell Street]] in 1837, one of the first in the Colony. Their residences were both on [[South Terrace, Adelaide]], almost adjacent; Duff moved from South Terrace around the end of 1846.\n\nThey dissolved their partnership in December 1840. Both had substantial land holdings; Duff purchased one of the original town acres at the corner of Currie Street and West Terrace and larger properties near the city.<ref name=brummitt/> He allowed his farmer tenants to pay their rent in bags of wheat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71618540 |title=Local News |newspaper=[[Southern Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=24 November 1843 |accessdate=26 May 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He donated part of his property \"Woodford\", near [[Magill, South Australia|Magill]], for St. George's Anglican Church. They had other properties further out: at Port Lincoln, and \"Woodford\" on the [[South Para River|Para River]], where he ran sheep. In 1837 he exported in four bales of wool to England \u2013 the first from South Australia. Duff and Hallett were early and generous contributors to the establishment of [[Holy Trinity Church, Adelaide|Trinity Church]].<ref name=brummitt/> \n \nIn 1838 Duff and his wife returned to England where their first child was born, and was christened at the church where they had been married (she was to be christened a second time, as Jessie Light Duff at Trinity Church, North Terrace, Adelaide, in honour of Colonel William Light). They returned to South Australia as fellow-passengers on the ''Asia'' with Dr. [[George Mayo]], with whom he developed a long-lasting friendship, arriving in July 1839.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\nDuff owned the [[schooner]] ''Waterwitch'', usually commanded by D. Talbert, which traded between [[Mauritius]], [[R\u00e9union|Bourbon]] and [[Port Adelaide]], also between Port Adelaide and [[Fremantle, Western Australia]]. She was lost with all hands on a return voyage which left Mauritius on 28 August September 1846. He also owned the [[barque]] ''Guiana'', which he took to Mauritius twice, and the ''Augustus'' which he also commanded on several Mauritius voyages.\n\nIn 1859, Captain Duff accepted the appointment of Harbourmaster and Lightkeeper at Glenelg, which he held for several years. One of his first duties was to decide on the suitability of [[Cape Willoughby]] for a lighthouse.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50247597 |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 June 1849 |accessdate=26 May 2015 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nHe died at his home at [[Glenelg, South Australia|New Glenelg]], and was buried at [[West Terrace Cemetery]]. Robert Gouger thought very highly of him, noting that \"\u2026 he appears to be a thorough sailor, decisive and skilful; he pays equal attention to all his passengers, has no favorites apparently, and therefore is a general favorite.\"<ref name=bound/> Light was also fulsome in his praise for Duff's seamanship and judgment.<ref name=brummitt/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=5 |The Duff SA Voyages\n|-\n!Ship\n!Departure\n!Port\n!Arrival\n!Notes\n|-\n||''Africaine'' || ||London||6 November 1836 || part of SA's \"First Fleet\"\n|-\n||''Africaine'' || ||Hobart||30 January 1837 ||\n|-\n||''Africaine'' || ||Launceston||14 July 1837 ||\n|-\n||''Sir Charles McCarthy'' || ||Launceston ||8 October 1837 || wrecked at Glenelg November 1837\n|-\n||''Asia'' || ||London ||16 July 1839 ||\n|-\n||''Waterwitch'' ||3 March 1840 ||Launceston || ||\n|-\n||''Guiana'' || ||Mauritius||27 July 1842 || first cargo landed at the new port\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||21 March 1844 ||Sydney||16 June 1844 || misreported as bound for Mauritius\n|-\n||''Guiana'' ||16 August 1844 ||Mauritius ||8 February 1845 ||\n|-\n||''Guiana'' || ||Hobart ||4 April 1846 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||5 February 1847 ||Mauritius ||26 June 1847 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' ||13 July 1847 ||Hobart ||16 September 1847 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' || ||Mauritius ||13 July 1848 ||\n|-\n||''Augustus'' || ||Hobart ||23 November 1848 ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Family==\nDuff married Anna? Anne? Eliza Turner ( \u2013 22 November 1854) on 29 June 1836. Their children included:\n*Jessie Light Duff (29 November 1838 \u2013 ) married William S. Miller of Parkside on 4 September 1861\n<!-- Charles Reginald 1840\u20131841 -->\n*John Finlay Duff, Jr.(4 December 1843 \u2013 October 1897)<!--married A. S. Duff--> lived at Glenelg. He died at Argyle Downs Station. W.A.\n<!--*son 3 October 1845\u2013 -->\n*Eliza Dixon Duff (c. 1848 \u2013 18 August 1921) married John W. Stafford ( \u2013 ) on 13 May 1871\n\nHe married again, to Mary Schroder ( \u2013 ) on 24 April 1862. He died six years later. Their children included:\n\n*Joseph Stilling Duff (1863 \u2013 21 January 1920) married Adelaide Lurina Capper in 1886. He was a theatre manager and accountant, died in [[Wellington, New Zealand]].\n*Stuart Duncan Duff (1866 \u2013 17 June 1941) married Mabel Annie Shephard on 6 April 1898, lived at Marion, then Brighton.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duff, John Finlay}}\n[[Category:Australian ship owners]]\n[[Category:Australian sailors]]\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at West Terrace Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "ScottDavis", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Finlay_Duff"}
{"title_page": "MLB at Field of Dreams", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball game\n| game = MLB at Field of Dreams\n| image = File:MLB at Field of Dreams.png\n| caption = \n| visitor = [[2020 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]\n| top1 =\n| top2 =\n| top3 =\n| top4 =\n| top5 =\n| top6 =\n| top7 =\n| top8 =\n| top9 =\n| visitor_r =\n| visitor_h =\n| visitor_e =\n| home = [[2020 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]\n| bot1 =\n| bot2 =\n| bot3 =\n| bot4 =\n| bot5 =\n| bot6 =\n| bot7 =\n| bot8 =\n| bot9 =\n| home_r =\n| home_h =\n| home_e =\n| date = August 13, 2020\n| venue = [[Field of Dreams (Dubuque County, Iowa)|Field of Dreams]]\n| city = [[Dyersville, Iowa]]\n| manager_visitor = [[Aaron Boone]]\n| manager_home = [[Rick Renteria]]\n| umpires =\n| attendance =\n| first_pitch = <!-- ceremonial first pitch, not time the game starts -->\n| television = [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]]\n| tv_announcers =\n| radio = \n| radio_announcers =\n| game_short        = \n| previous          = \n| next              = \n}}\n'''MLB at Field of Dreams''' is an upcoming regular season [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) game to be played on August 13, 2020, in [[Dyersville, Iowa]], during the [[2020 Major League Baseball season|2020 MLB season]].\n\nThe game will be between the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]], televised on [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]]. The game will be sponsored by [[GEICO]].<ref name=faq>{{cite web|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|title=Field of Dreams FAQ: Tickets and other details|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/field-of-dreams-game-tickets-and-faqs|website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe game will be the first game of a three game series, with the other two games being held at [[Guaranteed Rate Field]] in Chicago.<ref name=article/>  The Chicago White Sox will be deemed as the home team for the game, thus counting towards their home record. It will be the first ever MLB game in the state of Iowa.<ref name=article/> \n\n==Ballpark==\nThe game will be held at the filming location of the [[Field of Dreams|1989 baseball movie]], in Dyersville, Iowa. It will be the first Major League game in Dyersville. A temporary 8,000-seat ballpark will be constructed specifically for the game. The design of the ballpark, will pay homage to the White Sox home from 1910-90, [[Comiskey Park]], including the shape of the outfield and the bullpens beyond the center field fence. The right field wall will include windows to show the cornfields beyond the ballpark and will provide views of the movie set.<ref name=faq/><ref name=article>{{cite web|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|title=Yanks, White Sox to play at \u2018Field of Dreams\u2019|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/yankees-white-sox-game-at-field-of-dream-site|website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Game==\n===Line score===\n{{linescore\n| Date = August 13, 2020\n| Time = 6:20 p.m. ([[Central Time Zone|CST]])\n| Location = [[Field of Dreams (Dubuque County, Iowa)|Field of Dreams]]\n| Other = \n| Road = [[New York Yankees]]\n| RoadAbr = NYY\n| R1= &nbsp;| R2 = &nbsp;| R3 = &nbsp;| R4 = &nbsp;| R5 = &nbsp;| R6 = &nbsp;| R7 = &nbsp;| R8 = &nbsp;| R9 = &nbsp;| RR = &nbsp;| RH = &nbsp;| RE = &nbsp;\n| RSP = \n| Home = [[Chicago White Sox]]\n| HomeAbr = CWS\n| H1 = &nbsp;| H2 = &nbsp;| H3 = &nbsp;| H4 = &nbsp;| H5 = &nbsp;| H6 = &nbsp;| H7 = &nbsp;| H8 = &nbsp;| H9 = &nbsp;| HR =  &nbsp;| HH =  &nbsp;| HE = &nbsp;\n| HSP = \n| WP = \n| LP = \n| SV = \n| RoadHR = \n| HomeHR = \n| Attendance = \n| Notes = \n| BoxURL = https://www.mlb.com/gameday/yankees-vs-white-sox/2020/08/13/604327\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2020 MLB season by team}}\n{{2020 Notable MLB Games}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{Chicago White Sox}}\n{{Fox Major League Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MLB at Field of Dreams}}\n[[Category:2020 in sports in Iowa]]\n[[Category:2020 Major League Baseball season]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball games]]\n[[Category:August 2020 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball game\n| game = MLB at Field of Dreams\n| image = File:MLB at Field of Dreams.png\n| caption = \n| visitor = [[2020 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]\n| top1 =\n| top2 =\n| top3 =\n| top4 =\n| top5 =\n| top6 =\n| top7 =\n| top8 =\n| top9 =\n| visitor_r =\n| visitor_h =\n| visitor_e =\n| home = [[2020 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]\n| bot1 =\n| bot2 =\n| bot3 =\n| bot4 =\n| bot5 =\n| bot6 =\n| bot7 =\n| bot8 =\n| bot9 =\n| home_r =\n| home_h =\n| home_e =\n| date = August 13, 2020\n| venue = [[Field of Dreams (Dubuque County, Iowa)|Field of Dreams]]\n| city = [[Dyersville, Iowa]]\n| manager_visitor = [[Aaron Boone]]\n| manager_home = [[Rick Renteria]]\n| umpires =\n| attendance =\n| first_pitch = <!-- ceremonial first pitch, not time the game starts -->\n| television = [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]]\n| tv_announcers =\n| radio = \n| radio_announcers =\n| game_short        = \n| previous          = \n| next              = \n}}\n'''MLB at Field of Dreams''' is an upcoming regular season [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) game to be played on August 13, 2020, in [[Dyersville, Iowa]], during the [[2020 Major League Baseball season|2020 MLB season]].\n\nThe game will be between the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]], televised on [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]]. The game will be sponsored by [[GEICO]].<ref name=faq>{{cite web|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|title=Field of Dreams FAQ: Tickets and other details|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/field-of-dreams-game-tickets-and-faqs|website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe game will be the first game of a three game series, with the other two games being held at [[Guaranteed Rate Field]] in Chicago.<ref name=article/>  It will be the first ever MLB game in the state of Iowa.<ref name=article/> \n\n==Ballpark==\nThe game will be held at the filming location of the [[Field of Dreams|1989 baseball movie]], in Dyersville, Iowa. It will be the first Major League game in Dyersville. A temporary 8,000-seat ballpark will be constructed specifically for the game. The design of the ballpark, will pay homage to the White Sox home from 1910-90, [[Comiskey Park]], including the shape of the outfield and the bullpens beyond the center field fence. The right field wall will include windows to show the cornfields beyond the ballpark and will provide views of the movie set.<ref name=faq/><ref name=article>{{cite web|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|title=Yanks, White Sox to play at \u2018Field of Dreams\u2019|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/yankees-white-sox-game-at-field-of-dream-site|website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Game==\n===Line score===\n{{linescore\n| Date = August 13, 2020\n| Time = 6:20 p.m. ([[Central Time Zone|CST]])\n| Location = [[Field of Dreams (Dubuque County, Iowa)|Field of Dreams]]\n| Other = \n| Road = [[New York Yankees]]\n| RoadAbr = NYY\n| R1= &nbsp;| R2 = &nbsp;| R3 = &nbsp;| R4 = &nbsp;| R5 = &nbsp;| R6 = &nbsp;| R7 = &nbsp;| R8 = &nbsp;| R9 = &nbsp;| RR = &nbsp;| RH = &nbsp;| RE = &nbsp;\n| RSP = \n| Home = [[Chicago White Sox]]\n| HomeAbr = CWS\n| H1 = &nbsp;| H2 = &nbsp;| H3 = &nbsp;| H4 = &nbsp;| H5 = &nbsp;| H6 = &nbsp;| H7 = &nbsp;| H8 = &nbsp;| H9 = &nbsp;| HR =  &nbsp;| HH =  &nbsp;| HE = &nbsp;\n| HSP = \n| WP = \n| LP = \n| SV = \n| RoadHR = \n| HomeHR = \n| Attendance = \n| Notes = \n| BoxURL = https://www.mlb.com/gameday/yankees-vs-white-sox/2020/08/13/604327\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2020 MLB season by team}}\n{{2020 Notable MLB Games}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{Chicago White Sox}}\n{{Fox Major League Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MLB at Field of Dreams}}\n[[Category:2020 in sports in Iowa]]\n[[Category:2020 Major League Baseball season]]\n[